<table class="principles-table">
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Clarity over trendiness</strong></td>
      <td
        >Elegant systems are not those using the newest tools, but those whose
        constraints and trade-offs are well understood.</td
      >
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Scalability as a design property</strong></td>
      <td
        >Scalability is not added later. It is embedded in data modeling,
        communication patterns and failure strategy from the start.</td
      >
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Testing as structural integrity</strong></td>
      <td
        >Testing is not a safety net; it is part of the architecture. A system
        that cannot be tested properly is rarely well designed.</td
      >
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Performance with purpose</strong></td>
      <td
        >Low latency and resource efficiency matter when they create real
        product value — not as vanity metrics.</td
      >
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Maintainability as a strategic asset</strong></td>
      <td
        >Robust systems are those that survive team changes, shifting
        requirements and growth.</td
      >
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

